%N A302715 Decimal expansion of 2*sin(Pi/120).
%C A302715 This constant appears in a historic problem posed by Adriaan van Roomen (Adrianus Romanus) in his Ideae mathematicae from 1593, solved by Vi√®te. See the Havil reference, problem 3, pp. 69-74. See also the comments in A302711 with a link to Romanus book, Exemplum tertium.
%C A302715 The solution of the problem uses the special case of an identity R(45, 2*sin(Pi/120)) = 2*sin(3*Pi/8) = A179260 = 1.847759065022..., with a special case of monic Chebyshev polynomials of the first kind, named R, given in A127672.
%D A302715 Julian Havil, The Irrationals, A Story of the Numbers You Can't Count On, Princeton University Press, Princeton and Oxford, 2012, pp. 69-74.
%H A302715 Jason Bard, <a href="/A302715/b302715.txt">Table of n, a(n) for n = -1..1998</a>
%H A302715 <a href="/index/Ch#Cheby">Index entries for sequences related to Chebyshev polynomials</a>.
%F A302715 This constant is 2*sin(Pi/120) = sqrt(2 - sqrt(2 + sqrt(3/16) + sqrt(15/16) + sqrt(5/8 - sqrt(5/64)))) (this is the rewritten x given in the Havil reference on the bottom of page 69).
%e A302715 0.05235389661574630522122337110822532758678205536021727643757...
